@Nhawks17 asked for logs and pictures.  Without them, little can be done except ask you to check the install.  Which means you need to clean the old install out and do it from scratch to avoid keeping problems.  So here's how I do it.

Keep in mind SVE, Stock Visual Enhancements, as said in the original post, is @Nhawks17's port of  @pingopete's RVE, Realism Visual Overhaul.  Both include configs for @rbray89's EVE, Environmental Visual Effects.

The 3 parts of an SVE install are all included in the SVE install zip file, with 2 of them being from the mods EVE and Scatterer.

1. EVE plugins and shaders in the directory "GameData/EnvironmentalVisualEffects/"

This is included in the SVE download zip.  It is also available from the EVE topic via its Github release page in the "AnyCPU-EVE-Release.zip" archive.

2. EVE configuration.

For SVE this is located in the directory "GameData/StockVisualEnhancements/".  Its only source is from the SVE install zip.  However....

EVE itself has a default configuration which goes in the directory "GameData/BoulderCo/", installed from EVE's "AnyCPU-Configs-Release.zip".  For SVE, DO NOT INSTALL THIS.  If you have this directory, remove it for SVE.

As well, RVE provides an EVE configuration which goes in the directory "GameData/RVE/", installed from its download zip file.  Again, for SVE, DO NOT INSTALL THIS.  If you have this directory, remove it for SVE.

3. Scatterer mod in the directory "GameData/scatterer/"

Again, this is included in the SVE download zip.  It is also available from the Scatterer topic via its Spacedock release page.

Important note: SVE includes all of those 3 parts.  2 of those parts are the EVE plugins and shaders and the Scatter mod, as I describe under point 2 and 3.

If you want to upgrade the EVE plugins and shaders from its own topic, you have to remove the previous parts of EVE in "GameData/EnvironmentalVisualEffects/" first.

If you want to upgrade the Scatter mod from its own topic, you have to remove the old Scatterer mod files in "GameData/scatterer/" first.

Do not just overwrite.  When mods upgrade, they can remove or rename files and directories.  Overwriting leads to mixing files from multiple versions of a mod, always bad.

Note that @Nhawks17 works to make sure SVE works with the versions of EVE and Scatterer he includes.  Upgrading them independently can solve issues the upgraded code fixes, but it also can cause problems.  Upgrading has to be done properly.  And be sure to mention when they have been independently upgraded.

Spoiler

There's a lot that's improved with KSP 1.1+, but there's still issues with it (especially the wheels and legs).  Many mods have been updated, but many haven't.  KSP 1.1+ changed a lot from previous versions, including changing from Unity 4 to 5.  Mods written for previous KSP versions are more likely to break things in weird ways.  You have to be sure which ones will work and in which ways.  Older wheels and legs can't be used because their configs won't have the work-arounds for the wheel and leg bugs, only the stock parts and parts mods under active development have them.

To not have everything in KSP turn into a mess, you've got to mod and play simply and carefully to avoid hitting known and potential bugs. Everything has to be kept as simple as possible.  And take your time.

I really think you're going to have to work with a smaller set of mods for now and start again from scratch.  Do a clean install of KSP.  Check for the latest version of mods and stick to ones that have released for KSP 1.1.2 (or rarely a recompile that others say is working).  Start new careers or sandbox games.  And rebuilt your previous .craft files to avoid cruft biting you.  Build up your mods a few at a time and test, so you know what change made things go wrong.

And if you're talking about a total-conversion mods or set of mods, like Realism Overhaul, that has to be in its own separate install of KSP (you can have more than one, and you should never use the Steam download one except to copy elsewhere).  And with them, you have to follow their rules and guidelines about what mods they works with.  Total-conversion mods will commonly conflict with many other mods and you have to avoid that.  At least get them working first before you try to extend them with other mods.

And when things break, and you would like assistance, you have to do the homework or people won't be able to help.  That means logs, screenshots, .craft files as appropriate.  For a VFX fault, a picture is worth a thousand words of description.  The mods writers have seen it go wrong a lot and that picture will often tell them what your words can't.

Now, about SVE in particular.

Spoiler

What you're seem to be saying is you're using the EVE configs from both EVE and SVE together by mixing and matching.  It's not surprising you're getting artifacts like double clouds.   For the planet with double clouds, this combination of configs has at least 2 groups of files telling EVE to make clouds.  So EVE has made 2 sets of clouds.  It's just doing what you told it to.

@rbray89, @pingopete, and @Nhawks17 each have put together their own EVE configs.  Each of them are working to improve them, and @rbray89 EVE's plugins and shaders as well.  You can't just combine them without really understanding EVE configuration files and how to take separate parts of the configs and make sure they don't conflict, miss features, or duplicate them.  And when they do, how to merge them to give one config that shows what you want.  That's going to be about as much work as making a config from scratch.  And it's going to be a lot.

Back in the EVE 7-x code line with earlier versions of KSP, I installed @Astronomer's custom configs.  He worked very hard to customize and improve the stock config for EVE, as well as drawing on other mods like PlanetShine and TextureReplacer.  His zip files had the several different parts of the config split out, with variant parts you'd only install one of.  And the zip file was loaded with instructions about how to install all this.  From that, I could see how the parts of EVE's config were built up.  But I still customized it as little as possible.

I really think you should start with using just one of the EVE configs, either the stock one or SVE's.  Get that working.  Then, if that is working okay, and you really want to, very very carefully try metamodding that a tiny amount.  And see if it works.

@NemesisBosseret, dude, you're trying to do too much too fast, with too much customization.  I run as many mods as you do, but I've built up to it, I use a tool (JSGME) to install and remove mods, I've bashed file systems and code for years and I really really understand it and really really organize it well.  But I still I take it a bit at a time, because it's damn complex and I need to be careful.  I customize what I really need but as little as possible, mostly with ModuleManager custom configs, I document what I do, and I make sure I don't overwhelm meself.

More stuff in general, including my suggestion you need to do a clean reinstall.  And total-conversion mods like Realism Overhaul need their own separate install of KSP.

  Reveal hidden contents

There's a lot that's improved with KSP 1.1+, but there's still issues with it (especially the wheels and legs).  Many mods have been updated, but many haven't.  KSP 1.1+ changed a lot from previous versions, including changing from Unity 4 to 5.  Mods written for previous KSP versions are more likely to break things in weird ways.  You have to be sure which ones will work and in which ways.  Older wheels and legs can't be used because their configs won't have the work-arounds for the wheel and leg bugs, only the stock parts and parts mods under active development have them.

To not have everything in KSP turn into a mess, you've got to mod and play simply and carefully to avoid hitting known and potential bugs. Everything has to be kept as simple as possible.  And take your time.

I really think you're going to have to work with a smaller set of mods for now and start again from scratch.  Do a clean install of KSP.  Check for the latest version of mods and stick to ones that have released for KSP 1.1.2 (or rarely a recompile that others say is working).  Start new careers or sandbox games.  And rebuilt your previous .craft files to avoid cruft biting you.  Build up your mods a few at a time and test, so you know what change made things go wrong.

And if you're talking about a total-conversion mods or set of mods, like Realism Overhaul, that has to be in its own separate install of KSP (you can have more than one, and you should never use the Steam download one except to copy elsewhere).  And with them, you have to follow their rules and guidelines about what mods they works with.  Total-conversion mods will commonly conflict with many other mods and you have to avoid that.  At least get them working first before you try to extend them with other mods.

And when things break, and you would like assistance, you have to do the homework or people won't be able to help.  That means logs, screenshots, .craft files as appropriate.  For a VFX fault, a picture is worth a thousand words of description.  The mods writers have seen it go wrong a lot and that picture will often tell them what your words can't.

Now, about SVE in particular.

  Reveal hidden contents

What you're seem to be saying is you're using the EVE configs from both EVE and SVE together by mixing and matching.  It's not surprising you're getting artifacts like double clouds.   For the planet with double clouds, this combination of configs has at least 2 groups of files telling EVE to make clouds.  So EVE has made 2 sets of clouds.  It's just doing what you told it to.

@rbray89, @pingopete, and @Nhawks17 each have put together their own EVE configs.  Each of them are working to improve them, and @rbray89 EVE's plugins and shaders as well.  You can't just combine them without really understanding EVE configuration files and how to take separate parts of the configs and make sure they don't conflict, miss features, or duplicate them.  And when they do, how to merge them to give one config that shows what you want.  That's going to be about as much work as making a config from scratch.  And it's going to be a lot.

Back in the EVE 7-x code line with earlier versions of KSP, I installed @Astronomer's custom configs.  He worked very hard to customize and improve the stock config for EVE, as well as drawing on other mods like PlanetShine and TextureReplacer.  His zip files had the several different parts of the config split out, with variant parts you'd only install one of.  And the zip file was loaded with instructions about how to install all this.  From that, I could see how the parts of EVE's config were built up.  But I still customized it as little as possible.

I really think you should start with using just one of the EVE configs, either the stock one or SVE's.  Get that working.  Then, if that is working okay, and you really want to, very very carefully try metamodding that a tiny amount.  And see if it works.
